---
dops: v1
kind: tool

meta:
  name: makefile
  version: 1.0.0
  description: "Generate Makefiles for build automation"
  author: dojops
  license: MIT
  tags: [make, makefile, build, automation, compile]

input:
  fields:
    projectPath:
      type: string
      required: true
      description: "Root directory of the project"
    targets:
      type: string
      required: true
      description: "Description of build targets to create"
    environment:
      type: string

output:
  type: object
  required: [content]
  properties:
    content:
      type: string
      description: "Complete Makefile content as text"

files:
  - path: "{projectPath}/Makefile"
    format: raw
    source: llm
    dataPath: content

detection:
  paths: ["Makefile", "makefile", "GNUmakefile"]
  updateMode: true

verification:
  structural:
    - path: "content"
      required: true
      type: string
      message: "Makefile content is required"

  binary:
    command: "make -n -f Makefile"
    parser: make-dryrun
    timeout: 30000
    cwd: output

permissions:
  filesystem: write
  child_process: required
  network: none

scope:
  write: ["{projectPath}/Makefile"]

risk:
  level: LOW
  rationale: "Build automation changes are local"

execution:
  mode: generate
  deterministic: false
  idempotent: true

update:
  strategy: replace
  inputSource: file
  injectAs: existingContent
---
# Makefile

## Prompt

You are a build automation expert. Generate a Makefile as text.

You MUST respond with a JSON object containing a "content" field with the complete Makefile as a string.

The Makefile should:
- Use tab indentation for commands (CRITICAL — Makefiles require tabs, not spaces)
- Include .PHONY declarations for non-file targets
- Set .DEFAULT_GOAL for the main target
- Include common targets (build, test, clean, lint, help)
- Use variables for configurable values

Response format:
{
  "content": ".DEFAULT_GOAL := help\n\n.PHONY: build test clean lint help\n\nbuild:\n\tnpm run build\n\ntest:\n\tnpm test\n\nclean:\n\trm -rf dist node_modules\n\nlint:\n\tnpm run lint\n\nhelp:\n\t@echo \"Available targets:\"\n\t@echo \"  build  - Build the project\"\n\t@echo \"  test   - Run tests\"\n\t@echo \"  clean  - Clean build artifacts\"\n\t@echo \"  lint   - Run linter\"\n\t@echo \"  help   - Show this help\"\n"
}

IMPORTANT:
- "content" must contain the COMPLETE Makefile as a string
- Commands MUST be indented with TABS (\t), not spaces
- Include .PHONY for all non-file targets
- Include a help target
- Respond with valid JSON only, no markdown

## Update Prompt

You are a build automation expert. Update the existing Makefile.
Preserve existing targets and settings. Only add/modify what is requested.

--- EXISTING CONFIGURATION ---
{existingContent}
--- END EXISTING CONFIGURATION ---

Respond with a JSON object containing a "content" field with the complete updated Makefile.

IMPORTANT:
- Preserve ALL existing targets unless explicitly asked to remove them
- Maintain existing variables and .PHONY declarations
- Use tab indentation for commands
- Respond with valid JSON only, no markdown

## Examples

Given: "Makefile for a Go project with build, test, and docker targets"

```json
{
  "content": "BINARY_NAME := myapp\nGO := go\nDOCKER := docker\n\n.DEFAULT_GOAL := help\n\n.PHONY: build test clean lint docker-build docker-push help\n\nbuild:\n\t$(GO) build -o bin/$(BINARY_NAME) ./cmd/$(BINARY_NAME)\n\ntest:\n\t$(GO) test ./...\n\nclean:\n\trm -rf bin/\n\nlint:\n\tgolangci-lint run\n\ndocker-build:\n\t$(DOCKER) build -t $(BINARY_NAME):latest .\n\ndocker-push:\n\t$(DOCKER) push $(BINARY_NAME):latest\n\nhelp:\n\t@echo \"Available targets:\"\n\t@echo \"  build        - Build the binary\"\n\t@echo \"  test         - Run tests\"\n\t@echo \"  clean        - Clean build artifacts\"\n\t@echo \"  lint         - Run linter\"\n\t@echo \"  docker-build - Build Docker image\"\n\t@echo \"  docker-push  - Push Docker image\"\n\t@echo \"  help         - Show this help\"\n"
}
```

## Constraints

- Commands MUST use tab indentation (not spaces)
- Include .PHONY for all non-file targets
- Include a help target with descriptions
- Use variables for repeated values
- Maximum 30 targets per Makefile
- No hardcoded secrets or credentials

## Keywords

make, makefile, build, compile, automation, gnumake,
target, recipe, phony, clean, install, deploy
